  "extendedContent": [
    {
      "title": "Origins & Birth",
      "content": "The origin of Frigg, the Norse goddess of marriage, motherhood, and foresight, is somewhat veiled in mystery. While she is prominently featured in later Norse texts like the Prose Edda and the Poetic Edda, earlier sources offer less explicit detail about her parentage and early life. She is the wife of Odin, the Allfather, and together they reign over Asgard, the realm of the gods. Although her lineage is not definitively stated, scholarly interpretations suggest that Frigg may be connected to the earlier Germanic goddess Frija, further linking her to themes of love, fertility, and domesticity. The etymology of her name, meaning \"beloved,\" underscores her revered position within the Norse pantheon. Frigg's role as queen and her association with weaving and household management solidify her importance as a central figure in Norse cosmology and social structure."
    },
    {
      "title": "Major Myths & Stories",
      "content": "One of the most poignant stories involving Frigg centers on her love for her son, Baldr. When Baldr began to have prophetic dreams of his own death, Frigg, in her maternal concern, went throughout the world and extracted promises from every thing - fire, water, metal, stone, diseases, plants, animals - that they would not harm Baldr. However, she overlooked the mistletoe, deeming it too young and harmless to require an oath. The mischievous Loki discovered this oversight and fashioned a dart of mistletoe, which he then tricked Hodr, Baldr's blind brother, into throwing at him, resulting in Baldr's death. This tale highlights Frigg's protective nature and her deep grief. Another significant myth involves Frigg's attempts to protect her favorite people. She used her foresight and power to influence events, even going against the will of Odin on occasion, showcasing her strength and determination."
    },
    {
      "title": "Worship & Cult",
      "content": "Evidence of a dedicated cult of Frigg is limited, but her importance in Norse society is undeniable. As a goddess associated with marriage, family, and household management, Frigg was likely honored in domestic settings. Women would have sought her blessings for successful childbirth, marital harmony, and the smooth running of their households. Spindle whorls, associated with Frigg's role as a weaver, have been found in burial sites, suggesting a connection between Frigg and the afterlife. While there may not have been large-scale temples dedicated solely to Frigg, she was undoubtedly revered and invoked in conjunction with other deities, particularly Odin, in various rituals and ceremonies. Her association with Friday, Frigg's day, further indicates her prominent place in the Norse week and the cultural consciousness of the time. The veneration of Frigg underscores the importance of women and domesticity in Norse society."
    },
    {
      "title": "Legacy & Influence",
      "content": "Frigg's legacy extends beyond her immediate role in Norse mythology. Her name survives in the English word \"Friday,\" a testament to her enduring influence on language and culture. In modern paganism and Heathenry, Frigg remains a revered goddess, embodying the ideals of motherhood, marriage, and domesticity. She is often invoked in rituals related to these themes, and her wisdom and foresight are sought by those seeking guidance in their personal lives. Frigg serves as a powerful symbol of feminine strength, resilience, and the importance of family bonds. Her stories continue to resonate with contemporary audiences, offering insights into the values and beliefs of the ancient Norse people and providing a source of inspiration for those seeking to connect with their ancestral roots. Frigg's enduring presence in modern spirituality ensures that her legacy will continue to thrive for generations to come."
    }
  ],
